s bodies and education – the volume covers the social and political structure of the Ottoman Empire. It uses the innovative prism of children as social agents who are not only shaped by but also shape society, rather than being the passive recipients of their social environment.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aChildrenzBalkan PeninsulaxHistory. 0aChildrenzMiddle EastxHistory. 0aChildrenzTurkeyxHistory. 4aIslamic Studies. 7aHISTORY / Middle East / General.2bisacsh1 aAraz, Yahya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaroqhi, Suraiya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGara, Eleni, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeywood, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKayhan Elbirlik, Leyla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKokdaş, İrfan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKorić, Elma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLamdan, Ruth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoman, Nicoleta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTelci, Cahit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYavuz Velipaşaoğlu, Didem, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYazbak, Mahmoud, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYaşa, Fırat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYilmaz, Gülay, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aYılmaz, Gülay, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZachs, Fruma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZachs, Fruma, eeditor.